// SPEC 8.2 says of sort(): "element type must be Int/Float/String **at
// runtime**, else panic", and SPEC 2.5 says generics are type-erased with one
// compiled body serving all instantiations. So sorting a List[Int] through a
// generic function is a valid program: the runtime element type is Int and no
// panic should occur.
//
// The implementation instead rejects sort() on a generic receiver at COMPILE
// time:
//   error[E0322]: cannot sort the elements of values of generic type `T`
//     note: Socrates generics have no constraints; use a concrete type here
// which makes the spec'd runtime check unreachable. (Relatedly,
// `[true, false].sort()` is also a compile error E0322 rather than the
// runtime panic the spec describes.)
fn sort_it[T](xs: List[T]) -> List[T] { xs.sort() }
println(sort_it([3, 1, 2]));        //? expect: [1, 2, 3]
println(sort_it(["b", "a", "c"]));  //? expect: ["a", "b", "c"]
